250
00:14:05.682 --> 00:14:07.332
It wasn't like that this morning on my computer.

251
00:14:07.392 --> 00:14:07.792
But anyway,

252
00:14:09.412 --> 00:14:13.122
people with "lower African ancestry," which is on the

253
00:14:13.192 --> 00:14:16.892
left, clearly distinguished from people with higher

254
00:14:16.952 --> 00:14:20.761
African ancestry. So even at the level of gene expression

255
00:14:21.672 --> 00:14:25.372
in women with triple-negative breast cancer, you see two very different signatures.

256
00:14:25.742 --> 00:14:29.332
And when they deconvoluted these signatures, they found a number of

257
00:14:29.392 --> 00:14:30.832
immunological

258
00:14:32.192 --> 00:14:35.312
differences that were distinguishing between these groups.

259
00:14:35.692 --> 00:14:38.332
In particular, they found greater immune cell infiltration.

260
00:14:38.652 --> 00:14:41.712
So signals associated with immune cell infiltration in people with high African

261
00:14:41.772 --> 00:14:42.332
ancestry.

262
00:14:43.412 --> 00:14:46.832
But even though there was greater infiltration, they had a more immunosuppressive

263
00:14:46.892 --> 00:14:50.821
phenotype, suggesting that the cells that were coming in were more naive or

264
00:14:50.952 --> 00:14:51.532
suppressive

265
00:14:52.572 --> 00:14:55.452
than in European or other ancestry individuals.

266
00:14:55.772 --> 00:14:59.632
So once again, as you think about how we apply this, we're talking

267
00:14:59.652 --> 00:15:02.962
about hot tumors, cold tumors. We're talking about immunotherapy,

268
00:15:03.312 --> 00:15:06.752
understanding the immunological environment within which you're trying to deploy

269
00:15:06.792 --> 00:15:10.481
these is really important, and we cannot assume that everybody is the

270
00:15:10.512 --> 00:15:13.952
same. And so it's important to understand these at an ancestry level.

271
00:15:15.152 --> 00:15:17.352
Now, moving further into the continent.

272
00:15:18.272 --> 00:15:21.692
A part of what I said in the beginning was there's a need to localize some of this

273
00:15:21.732 --> 00:15:24.572
research. So this is a study from Kenya, looking at

274
00:15:26.112 --> 00:15:29.511
a small number of African Americans, Caucasian Americans, and then Kenyan

275
00:15:29.572 --> 00:15:33.032
individuals. And once again, looking at

276
00:15:33.132 --> 00:15:36.732
RNA-seq data, looking at transcriptomic data of people with triple-negative breast

277
00:15:36.792 --> 00:15:40.592
cancer, and clearly showing distinctions between

278
00:15:40.632 --> 00:15:42.612
Kenyan individuals and African Americans.

279
00:15:43.072 --> 00:15:46.312
So this once again makes, as I showed you earlier on, Africans are very diverse.

280
00:15:46.772 --> 00:15:48.972
African Americans are an admixed population.

281
00:15:49.512 --> 00:15:52.492
Many African Americans trace ancestry to West Africa.

282
00:15:52.902 --> 00:15:56.672
And so here you have African Americans compared to East Africans, and you can see

283
00:15:56.712 --> 00:16:00.402
significant differences. So at the beginning, I

284
00:16:00.432 --> 00:16:03.832
mentioned how most of the African data we have currently in genomic

285
00:16:03.892 --> 00:16:06.172
databases comes from African American individuals.

286
00:16:06.212 --> 00:16:10.132
You can see how that is not a good surrogate for individuals across the whole

287
00:16:10.172 --> 00:16:13.892
of Africa. So it's important that we begin to broaden the base of

288
00:16:13.912 --> 00:16:16.571
data that's coming in. And that is beginning to happen.

289
00:16:16.612 --> 00:16:19.432
This is a paper that was just published last year in "Nature Comm"

290
00:16:20.372 --> 00:16:23.972
for the first GWAS of continental Black African breast cancer

291
00:16:24.032 --> 00:16:25.132
patients. So it took us

292
00:16:26.231 --> 00:16:29.732
till 2025 to do the first proper GWAS of breast cancer in

293
00:16:30.212 --> 00:16:32.552
African women. So it's done in South Africa.

294
00:16:33.152 --> 00:16:34.272
And interestingly, they

295
00:16:35.572 --> 00:16:39.392
identified two novel loci that were actually not

296
00:16:39.472 --> 00:16:41.252
found in data from West African people.

297
00:16:41.612 --> 00:16:44.552
So this is a Southern African cohort, and you can see identifying

298
00:16:44.632 --> 00:16:46.292
unique

299
00:16:48.032 --> 00:16:51.672
loci, risk loci that would not be

300
00:16:51.752 --> 00:16:55.512
found in a typical West African or indeed African American

301
00:16:55.952 --> 00:16:59.822
ancestry population. And actually demonstrated in this

302
00:16:59.852 --> 00:17:03.632
paper that polygenic risk scores developed on primarily

303
00:17:03.672 --> 00:17:06.812
European data performed very poorly in this population.

304
00:17:06.833 --> 00:17:10.222
So once again, the applications of the work we do, we can't just

305
00:17:10.252 --> 00:17:13.802
transplant now even polygenic risk scores from

306
00:17:13.812 --> 00:17:17.712
populations in Europe or North America that are predominantly European to

307
00:17:18.212 --> 00:17:20.572
people in Africa. These scores tend to underperform.

308
00:17:22.853 --> 00:17:26.472
This is a study that was done in Nigeria, also quite

309
00:17:26.532 --> 00:17:27.032
recently.

310
00:17:27.853 --> 00:17:31.592
Once again, looking at breast cancer, in this case,

311
00:17:31.832 --> 00:17:35.432
looking at a panel of 50 cancer-related genes.

312
00:17:35.492 --> 00:17:38.672
So using the Illumina Amplicore Cancer Hotspot Panel.

313
00:17:38.912 --> 00:17:42.832
It was done in Solomon Rotimi's group in Covenant University in Nigeria.

314
00:17:43.612 --> 00:17:45.162
And what they managed to do was

315
00:17:46.292 --> 00:17:48.072
paired germline and somatic

316
00:17:49.612 --> 00:17:52.152
applicant-based sequencing, identify a novel

317
00:17:53.232 --> 00:17:57.112
germline variant in TP53. Now, I think that on its

318
00:17:57.152 --> 00:18:01.112
own is quite nice, but I think this also speaks to the ability to do this kind of

319
00:18:01.572 --> 00:18:05.352
work in Nigeria. And I think that was part of what they were

320
00:18:05.412 --> 00:18:09.352
proving was as we think about access to immunotherapies,

321
00:18:09.412 --> 00:18:12.892
we need to also have the ability to do genomic testing in these

322
00:18:12.932 --> 00:18:13.412
contexts

323
00:18:14.272 --> 00:18:17.732
locally. And so I think this was an important first sign that you

324
00:18:18.172 --> 00:18:20.792
could do pretty high-quality genomic testing in

325
00:18:20.832 --> 00:18:24.784
Nigeria.Before I get to TACA, this is the last thing

326
00:18:24.844 --> 00:18:28.744
I will show you. This is a study we did, currently under revision,

327
00:18:29.604 --> 00:18:32.824
where we did a retrospective whole exome study in Northern Nigeria.

328
00:18:32.904 --> 00:18:34.884
Northern Nigeria are predominantly Hausa people.

329
00:18:35.424 --> 00:18:39.304
Most of the Nigeria data in 1000 Genomes and in even HG

330
00:18:39.364 --> 00:18:42.604
Africa is Yoruba. So actually, when you think of Africa, they just use Yoruba,

331
00:18:42.944 --> 00:18:45.084
which is one ethnic group in Nigeria.

332
00:18:45.944 --> 00:18:49.864
And so I think this is probably the first time, at least that I've seen, that Hausa

333
00:18:49.884 --> 00:18:53.584
people have been sequenced. And I think the

334
00:18:53.624 --> 00:18:56.564
takeaway here, here we didn't have access to blood, so we couldn't do germline

335
00:18:56.624 --> 00:18:59.464
sequencing. We could only do somatic from FFP samples.

336
00:18:59.804 --> 00:19:03.104
So calling novel mutations, somatic mutations is a bit challenging.

337
00:19:03.524 --> 00:19:06.004
One of the reviewers has let us know that, so we're trying to see how.

338
00:19:06.704 --> 00:19:10.584
And actually, we used a Yoruba as our reference, and

339
00:19:10.624 --> 00:19:14.484
the reviewer called that out, which I thought was kind of cute, considering we

340
00:19:14.504 --> 00:19:15.944
were trying to do this for the first time.

341
00:19:15.964 --> 00:19:19.914
And yet, the pushback from a reviewer is that why are you using Yoruba when

342
00:19:19.984 --> 00:19:21.764
these are from Northern Nigeria and probably not.

343
00:19:22.064 --> 00:19:23.624
Perhaps the reviewer is a Nigerian, I don't know.

344
00:19:24.624 --> 00:19:28.504
But anyway, it is a valid point. We found a large number

345
00:19:28.564 --> 00:19:30.804
of seemingly novel variants.

346
00:19:31.624 --> 00:19:33.804
And even within cancer known genes, we found a lot of--

347
00:19:34.824 --> 00:19:38.104
67% of the 56 samples harbored novel

348
00:19:38.424 --> 00:19:42.324
variants in known cancer genes. So I think it just paints a picture of how

349
00:19:42.384 --> 00:19:45.404
little we understand about cancers in these populations.

350
00:19:46.724 --> 00:19:49.884
So I've tried to set the stage to tell you

351
00:19:50.344 --> 00:19:54.304
ancestry is important in cancer, and we're battling both

352
00:19:54.324 --> 00:19:58.264
the fact that we have African ancestry individuals being incredibly diverse,

353
00:19:58.424 --> 00:20:01.084
and we also have the least amount of data for those populations.

354
00:20:02.244 --> 00:20:05.524
And the truth is you can do small studies over and over again.

355
00:20:05.564 --> 00:20:07.124
At the end of the day, sometimes you need volume.

356
00:20:07.864 --> 00:20:11.204
TCGA is big for a reason. UK Biobank is big for a reason.

357
00:20:11.244 --> 00:20:11.394
Your

358
00:20:14.124 --> 00:20:16.024
N needs to be big enough to have sufficient power to

359
00:20:16.924 --> 00:20:20.784
understand these associations. And so a couple of years ago, we

360
00:20:20.844 --> 00:20:22.674
had this idea that we're not going to wait

361
00:20:23.644 --> 00:20:26.584
for our governments to figure out that we need to do a TCGA for Africa.

362
00:20:26.664 --> 00:20:29.184
We're going to try to do one ourselves. And so we called ours TACA.

363
00:20:30.064 --> 00:20:33.984
It's an ambitious project to ultimately generate 15,000 genomes of African

364
00:20:34.064 --> 00:20:37.944
ancestry individuals from really paired genomes from 7,500 people.

365
00:20:38.884 --> 00:20:41.664
Phase one has begun, thanks to a partnership with Roche.

366
00:20:42.224 --> 00:20:45.984
So we are currently funded to generate 3,000 genomes from

367
00:20:46.024 --> 00:20:49.964
1,500 people. These are whole genomes, paired blood, and

368
00:20:50.064 --> 00:20:53.904
somatic. And this would be the largest collection of African

369
00:20:53.964 --> 00:20:57.864
genomes to date. So we're quite excited by that, but obviously,

370
00:20:58.304 --> 00:20:59.704
there's a lot more that we'd like to do.

371
00:21:00.844 --> 00:21:02.944
So prospective recruitment for TACA has begun.

372
00:21:03.064 --> 00:21:06.764
We're currently recruiting in Côte d'Ivoire, in Ghana, in

373
00:21:06.784 --> 00:21:09.004
Nigeria, in Kenya, and the Seychelles.

374
00:21:09.104 --> 00:21:12.644
That's the dot on the side. So the Seychelles islands

375
00:21:12.984 --> 00:21:16.944
off the east coast of Africa. And we're currently waiting for-- Actually, I

376
00:21:16.964 --> 00:21:20.604
was informed this morning that we got IRB for Namibia, so I could change

377
00:21:20.624 --> 00:21:21.444
Namibia to green,

378
00:21:22.264 --> 00:21:25.973
to darker green. But we're also about to start, hopefully, in South Africa and in

379
00:21:26.044 --> 00:21:29.864
Zimbabwe, and also in Uganda. So we've currently recruited over

380
00:21:29.904 --> 00:21:31.224
500 individuals,

381
00:21:33.064 --> 00:21:36.944
collecting blood and tissue, as well as detailed clinical information, and the

382
00:21:36.984 --> 00:21:39.624
sequencing is ongoing. And the work I'm going to show you next is...

383
00:21:40.004 --> 00:21:43.324
I don't have to go-- The work I'll be showing you, the analysis is done by those

384
00:21:43.384 --> 00:21:44.784
four post-docs

385
00:21:46.124 --> 00:21:47.284
from Yamachi.

386
00:21:48.924 --> 00:21:52.324
So very quickly, the demographics of our

387
00:21:53.984 --> 00:21:55.593
TACA participants are as follows.

388
00:21:55.704 --> 00:21:59.274
Majority of them so far are breast cancer patients, although we are now

389
00:21:59.844 --> 00:22:01.564
actively recruiting colorectal cancer.

390
00:22:02.344 --> 00:22:05.404
So the colorectal numbers started-- We started recruiting colorectal this year, so

391
00:22:05.444 --> 00:22:08.824
those numbers should be going up over time. And a small number of lung.

392
00:22:08.904 --> 00:22:12.704
Lung is challenging in our context. Not many biopsies are done.

393
00:22:12.784 --> 00:22:15.044
It's often confused with tuberculosis.

394
00:22:15.524 --> 00:22:19.084
But we figure it's worth looking. So we are trying to get some lung.

395
00:22:19.624 --> 00:22:22.164
But most of the samples we have so far are breast cancer patients.

396
00:22:22.224 --> 00:22:26.164
You can see, as you would expect, many people present late, so

397
00:22:26.244 --> 00:22:29.544
stage III and stage IV predominate in every country.

398
00:22:31.384 --> 00:22:35.244
And that is well understood in the African context, where people don't

399
00:22:35.304 --> 00:22:39.284
often present very early. Women typically show up with very significant tumors,

400
00:22:39.844 --> 00:22:43.614
unlike what you'd find in countries like the U.S., where there's

401
00:22:43.744 --> 00:22:47.504
a bit more early prevention. And you can see the average

402
00:22:47.544 --> 00:22:51.214
ages among countries, somewhere in the late 40s to early 50s.

403
00:22:51.264 --> 00:22:55.254
Although we have had, I think our youngest participant was 22 with

404
00:22:55.304 --> 00:22:58.984
stage IV breast cancer, which is also not that unusual in the African

405
00:22:59.044 --> 00:22:59.524
context.

406
00:23:01.164 --> 00:23:04.344
We are looking at subtypes, and here an interesting picture is

407
00:23:04.404 --> 00:23:08.124
forming. We all know about triple-negative breast cancer being

408
00:23:08.164 --> 00:23:10.924
predominant in this country in African American women.

409
00:23:11.384 --> 00:23:14.384
We're seeing a pattern where triple-negative breast cancer seems to be more

410
00:23:14.424 --> 00:23:18.384
prevalent in Ghana and Nigeria, two West African countries, as compared to

411
00:23:18.424 --> 00:23:21.204
Kenya, which is East Africa, which has more luminal B.

412
00:23:21.624 --> 00:23:24.764
You can see the Seychelles has hardly any triple-negative

413
00:23:25.564 --> 00:23:28.504
breast cancer. Obviously, these numbers are still relatively small.

414
00:23:29.254 --> 00:23:32.504
But once again, there's not that much data out there, so this also represents some

415
00:23:32.544 --> 00:23:35.624
of the first cancer epidemiological data of this kind, of this

416
00:23:35.664 --> 00:23:39.604
quality. So as we build up TACA to 1,000, 2,000 breast cancer

417
00:23:39.614 --> 00:23:43.114
patients, we'll have a very clear idea of the geographic distribution of

418
00:23:43.144 --> 00:23:46.284
subtypes, which I think might be a very interesting area of study.

419
00:23:48.184 --> 00:23:51.964
And so sequencing has begun. We're doing whole genome

420
00:23:52.204 --> 00:23:55.024
sequencing on NovaSeq X Plus. We're doing all of this in Accra.

421
00:23:55.284 --> 00:23:55.644
So we

422
00:23:56.664 --> 00:23:58.624
figured out the logistics and the regulatory

423
00:23:59.564 --> 00:24:01.324
sort of impediments in moving samples around.

424
00:24:01.384 --> 00:24:02.724
So all our samples come to Accra

425
00:24:03.684 --> 00:24:06.444
and are sequenced at our lab in Accra.

426
00:24:07.984 --> 00:24:08.244
And

427
00:24:09.344 --> 00:24:12.984
when you do stuff from Africa, you often have to answer the questions of quality

428
00:24:13.044 --> 00:24:15.484
and how good things are. So we just take that on head-on.

429
00:24:15.544 --> 00:24:19.416
I figured I'd put a couple of slides for that.Fine, we understand

