00:26:25.456 --> 00:26:29.036
as much TMB. In this cohort, at least, our TMB seems in

469
00:26:29.076 --> 00:26:30.776
line with what has been seen.

470
00:26:32.336 --> 00:26:34.556
And then looking at sort of the mutational profiles.

471
00:26:34.616 --> 00:26:38.296
These slides are very fresh, so we're still analyzing data as more

472
00:26:38.336 --> 00:26:42.256
sequencing comes in. But we're seeing what appear to be differences in

473
00:26:42.336 --> 00:26:46.006
signature between subtypes, which would agree with what others have

474
00:26:46.016 --> 00:26:46.525
reported.

475
00:26:48.096 --> 00:26:51.536
And of course, as I said, the geographic distribution of these subtypes suggests

476
00:26:51.576 --> 00:26:52.436
that there may be some

477
00:26:53.516 --> 00:26:57.496
inherent differences from ancestry that determine which subtypes present in

478
00:26:57.536 --> 00:26:58.296
different places.

479
00:26:59.856 --> 00:27:01.696
We're also finding a number of enriched drivers.

480
00:27:01.796 --> 00:27:05.476
So our main interest in this is can we identify novel drivers in these

481
00:27:05.496 --> 00:27:07.865
populations that, quite frankly, have never been studied before?

482
00:27:08.476 --> 00:27:10.316
Some of these populations have never been sequenced.

