00:27:11.016 --> 00:27:14.716
And certainly have never had cancer, breast cancer, or any other cancer sequenced.

484
00:27:15.136 --> 00:27:19.025
So this is also very preliminary, but we are showing TP53,

485
00:27:19.236 --> 00:27:22.876
so it fits with the idea that African ancestry individuals tend to have

486
00:27:23.176 --> 00:27:26.816
enrichment in TP53 mutations. But we are identifying a number of

487
00:27:26.916 --> 00:27:30.616
other potential drivers that appear to be much more enriched in our

488
00:27:30.626 --> 00:27:33.956
populations than they are, for instance, on the cBioPortal, which

489
00:27:34.436 --> 00:27:38.176
represents existing databases. So a lot more work needs to be done, but we are

490
00:27:38.236 --> 00:27:40.596
finding that there are certain targets that...

491
00:27:42.096 --> 00:27:45.656
or certain drivers that appear to be over-represented in our populations and

492
00:27:45.716 --> 00:27:47.016
underrepresented in others.

493
00:27:47.856 --> 00:27:51.416
And this is just a couple of them, where actually we're finding subtype-specific

494
00:27:51.456 --> 00:27:53.336
differences. So for

495
00:27:54.876 --> 00:27:58.756
LEP R or leptin receptor, we find that they're over-represented in

496
00:27:58.816 --> 00:28:00.566
TNBCs, but not in the luminal.

497
00:28:01.476 --> 00:28:05.256
Whereas for KRTAP10-6, it's higher in luminal

498
00:28:05.596 --> 00:28:09.556
versus TNBC. So this is all very preliminary, but I think we're showing that

499
00:28:09.576 --> 00:28:12.536
there are subtype-specific differences within our population, but there's also

500
00:28:12.556 --> 00:28:16.516
enrichment within our population relative to primarily European ancestry groups.

501
00:28:17.376 --> 00:28:21.276
So this is where I will conclude. I think the point I'm

502
00:28:21.316 --> 00:28:22.716
trying to make is

503
00:28:23.716 --> 00:28:27.316
including African genomic data in cancer research is not a matter of

504
00:28:27.396 --> 00:28:30.946
inclusion or diversity or whatever word you may choose to use.

505
00:28:31.416 --> 00:28:35.085
It is good science. Because there's a lot we don't understand about cancer among

506
00:28:35.176 --> 00:28:38.956
everyone, and understanding it better in these diverse populations will help

507
00:28:39.296 --> 00:28:40.176
improve how we

508
00:28:40.976 --> 00:28:44.956
do research in cancer. So whether it's identifying novel mutations for risk

509
00:28:44.976 --> 00:28:47.656
prediction, novel clinically actionable variants,

510
00:28:48.896 --> 00:28:52.556
better annotation of VUSs. There's a huge problem in

511
00:28:52.596 --> 00:28:56.516
underrepresented minority patients who are all classified as VUS.

512
00:28:56.556 --> 00:29:00.476
In fact, the reason the Ministry of Health in the Seychelles signed on to TACA

513
00:29:00.516 --> 00:29:04.456
is because they are actually a high-income country. They have universal healthcare.

514
00:29:04.516 --> 00:29:08.446
Everybody with cancer gets sequenced or gets a panel done in the Seychelles, and

515
00:29:08.476 --> 00:29:12.396
yet all the results they get back are VUSs. So they're really frustrated by that.

516
00:29:12.456 --> 00:29:16.296
So they agreed to sign on to TACA because they wanted to sequence these people

517
00:29:16.636 --> 00:29:19.196
to understand, "Why do we keep getting these?

518
00:29:19.446 --> 00:29:22.856
What are these variants that we're getting?" So that,

519
00:29:23.436 --> 00:29:27.376
once again, shows access. If you don't include it in the original data, even if you

520
00:29:27.396 --> 00:29:31.156
can afford these tests, they're of limited value because they give you

521
00:29:31.196 --> 00:29:32.536
data that's really not actionable.

522
00:29:34.396 --> 00:29:37.656
So I'll end here with talking about localizing research.

523
00:29:37.776 --> 00:29:40.256
It's important that we study underrepresented

524
00:29:40.796 --> 00:29:44.756
populations in this country and in Europe and other high-income countries.

525
00:29:44.776 --> 00:29:48.556
But we also need to work towards building capacity in these locations so that some

526
00:29:48.616 --> 00:29:49.916
of this research can be done locally.

527
00:29:50.376 --> 00:29:53.256
Because if all we do is study them in our labs in

528
00:29:54.236 --> 00:29:58.076
high-income countries, we will understand these diseases better, but we'll not

529
00:29:58.136 --> 00:30:02.036
build the infrastructure required to ensure that access to these end products

530
00:30:02.076 --> 00:30:04.256
of this research is available locally.

531
00:30:04.416 --> 00:30:07.976
And so that's work that we are trying to do at Yamachi and

532
00:30:08.056 --> 00:30:11.736
obviously with collaborators, including Eresh and CSIR.

533
00:30:12.556 --> 00:30:16.126
So I'd just like to acknowledge all the hospitals that have supported us across

534
00:30:16.156 --> 00:30:19.536
multiple countries. It's a big leap to work with an unproven

535
00:30:19.556 --> 00:30:20.356
startup.

536
00:30:21.256 --> 00:30:24.176
But they've taken that leap with us.

537
00:30:24.196 --> 00:30:28.036
We have a number of institutes that have also worked with us and also a number

538
00:30:28.176 --> 00:30:31.944
of... technology platforms and obviously Roche in partnering with

539
00:30:32.004 --> 00:30:35.724
us on TACA. But most importantly, the study participants, many of whom are

540
00:30:35.784 --> 00:30:39.624
late-stage patients with very few options, no access to clinical trials,

541
00:30:40.184 --> 00:30:44.024
probably a good number of our cohort will not survive

542
00:30:44.064 --> 00:30:46.284
very long from the time we see them.

543
00:30:46.304 --> 00:30:49.844
But they sign on and consent because they hope that this sacrifice will help

544
00:30:49.864 --> 00:30:50.404
someone else

545
00:30:51.344 --> 00:30:54.664
in the future, and so really want to honor that contribution.

546
00:30:54.684 --> 00:30:58.504
So thank you very much, and we'll hand over to Irechen for

547
00:30:58.544 --> 00:31:00.584
the next talk. Thank you.

548
00:31:15.444 --> 00:31:16.044
Hey, thanks, Yo.

549
00:31:17.244 --> 00:31:18.984
Thank you everyone for coming here quickly.

550
00:31:20.344 --> 00:31:24.224
So my talk is going to be a lot different from what

551
00:31:24.344 --> 00:31:26.344
Yo just presented, so let's get into it.

552
00:31:27.184 --> 00:31:28.004
No disclosures.

553
00:31:30.904 --> 00:31:33.783
I was actually going to stand here for two minutes and say absolutely nothing.

554
00:31:35.124 --> 00:31:39.104
Just let us take that two minutes and to realize that someone would've just lost

555
00:31:39.144 --> 00:31:39.504
their life

556
00:31:40.544 --> 00:31:41.804
to cancer on the African continent.

557
00:31:43.444 --> 00:31:44.764
Yeah, that's actually quite staggering.

558
00:31:44.964 --> 00:31:46.844
I think that's more than double what it is in the USA.

559
00:31:48.444 --> 00:31:52.324
By 2030, we expect that number to rise to 1.5 million

560
00:31:52.334 --> 00:31:52.944
new cases,

561
00:31:54.404 --> 00:31:55.844
which is also quite staggering.

562
00:31:57.984 --> 00:32:01.684
70% of the global deaths occur in low to middle-income countries.

563
00:32:02.184 --> 00:32:03.304
We really carry the burden.

564
00:32:05.464 --> 00:32:07.884
You've heard this probably many times already this week.

565
00:32:08.444 --> 00:32:12.384
Less than 2% of the global cancer genomics databases come

566
00:32:12.424 --> 00:32:14.504
from people of African descent.

567
00:32:15.774 --> 00:32:19.464
That essentially means that entire continent is invisible to science from

