00:32:19.544 --> 00:32:20.764
a genomics perspective.

569
00:32:21.644 --> 00:32:25.244
And here I am about to speak about proteomics, and if you think about that, there's

570
00:32:25.284 --> 00:32:25.884
probably,

571
00:32:27.724 --> 00:32:31.164
I don't know, 0.1% of all proteomics data sets

572
00:32:31.174 --> 00:32:31.824
represented

573
00:32:32.964 --> 00:32:33.384
globally.

574
00:32:35.924 --> 00:32:39.854
What we found is that there's around three to six times high mortality rates

575
00:32:40.224 --> 00:32:43.464
for some cancers versus the global average if you look at African patients.

576
00:32:44.154 --> 00:32:48.144
And this is mostly driven by late detection and biology that we really don't

577
00:32:48.184 --> 00:32:48.684
understand.

578
00:32:49.544 --> 00:32:53.124
And what we're trying to do from a proteomics level is to address that

579
00:32:53.164 --> 00:32:56.864
question. One, can we identify cancers

580
00:32:56.904 --> 00:33:00.844
earlier? And two, can we just understand what is

581
00:33:00.864 --> 00:33:03.604
really happening? What is different in our people versus the rest of the world?

582
00:33:05.924 --> 00:33:09.564
So you've heard this from Yo, and you've seen really nice data that

583
00:33:09.644 --> 00:33:13.464
African genetic architecture is completely different from the rest of the

584
00:33:13.524 --> 00:33:13.804
world.

585
00:33:15.144 --> 00:33:18.644
There's things that are very unique to the African continent, the environment, the

586
00:33:18.704 --> 00:33:22.564
diet, the microbiome, social determinants, and these are many things that

587
00:33:22.584 --> 00:33:24.324
we don't really consider

588
00:33:25.264 --> 00:33:29.204
all too well when we do science on the African continent, or when

589
00:33:29.444 --> 00:33:31.724
outsiders look at the African continent science being done.

590
00:33:33.824 --> 00:33:37.684
Proteomics is what I do and have been doing for the most part of

591
00:33:37.724 --> 00:33:38.164
my career.

592
00:33:39.664 --> 00:33:41.964
And this is something that can really bridge some of these gaps.

593
00:33:43.244 --> 00:33:47.013
It enables us to really get an understanding of the post-translational

594
00:33:47.044 --> 00:33:48.424
biology. What is really happening?

595
00:33:49.884 --> 00:33:52.654
It is a functional layer that bridges genotype and phenotype,

596
00:33:53.504 --> 00:33:57.004
and again, as I mentioned in the very beginning, the number

597
00:33:57.064 --> 00:34:00.964
of data sets for proteomics specifically on the African continent

598
00:34:00.984 --> 00:34:03.184
is almost zero. It's negligible.

599
00:34:04.004 --> 00:34:07.984
So what we found that works really nicely is that collaboration, particularly in

600
00:34:08.024 --> 00:34:11.705
South Africa, is great because there's really nice pipelines that have been

601
00:34:11.784 --> 00:34:15.484
built and biobanks, and we have actually the expertise

602
00:34:15.944 --> 00:34:17.504
to be able to address this critical gap.

603
00:34:20.004 --> 00:34:23.364
So let me just do a little bit of punting of proteomics.

604
00:34:23.484 --> 00:34:27.423
Why proteomics? So everyone knows why the genome is important.

605
00:34:27.964 --> 00:34:31.765
We have around 20,000 genes, where we can get some kind of information on

606
00:34:31.804 --> 00:34:35.165
variants and mutations, and the transcriptome, which is

607
00:34:35.685 --> 00:34:39.644
around 100,000 transcripts, where you can get an idea of the gene expression level.

608
00:34:40.484 --> 00:34:44.404
And then the wonderful proteome, which has something like a million proteo forms.

609
00:34:44.944 --> 00:34:48.344
And we have decided to work in that area specifically.

610
00:34:49.504 --> 00:34:50.984
So what is the advantages of

611
00:34:52.404 --> 00:34:54.444
proteomics and understanding the proteome?

612
00:34:55.284 --> 00:34:58.744
This really captures PTMs, post-translational modifications.

613
00:34:58.914 --> 00:35:02.484
It reveals active protein-protein interaction networks in real tumors.

614
00:35:02.544 --> 00:35:06.424
So this is not predicted stuff. This is actually measuring the effect of molecules.

615
00:35:07.444 --> 00:35:09.184
It gives you a direct readout of signaling states.

616
00:35:09.934 --> 00:35:13.524
And increasingly what we are finding in the studies that we do is that there are

617
00:35:13.604 --> 00:35:17.524
Africa-specific or Africa-unique biomarkers which could potentially lead

618
00:35:17.604 --> 00:35:19.964
to novel drug targets for African patients.

619
00:35:21.924 --> 00:35:25.804
So here I just want to touch on maybe four studies

620
00:35:25.844 --> 00:35:28.944
that have been done very recently.

621
00:35:29.584 --> 00:35:33.214
The common thing from all of these studies is that they've all been done through

622
00:35:33.304 --> 00:35:36.844
our research center at the CSIR, where we've been doing

623
00:35:36.884 --> 00:35:39.964
proteomics for the best part of 15 to 20 years now.

624
00:35:41.304 --> 00:35:44.524
So it'll be a gallbladder study, a prostate cancer study,

625
00:35:44.924 --> 00:35:46.864
pancreatic cancer, and breast.

626
00:35:48.004 --> 00:35:50.244
And really some of these cancers are some of

627
00:35:51.704 --> 00:35:55.464
the cancer types that are the most prevalent in Southern

628
00:35:55.504 --> 00:35:58.484
Africa and really have the most devastation.

629
00:36:00.504 --> 00:36:02.164
So, the breast cancer study.

630
00:36:04.304 --> 00:36:07.104
If you look at the five-year survival rate for the breast cancers,

631
00:36:08.944 --> 00:36:12.884
we have around 40% versus 90% in

632
00:36:12.944 --> 00:36:14.964
the US, which is absolutely staggering.

633
00:36:16.324 --> 00:36:20.094
Yo spoke about the subtypes that are apparent, but in our study, we found that

